{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/732"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.63,0.18,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67789"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/732"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44473"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67789"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is referred by her General Practitioner to the Emergency Department due to concerns about systemic symptoms from a suspected urinary tract infection. She has a history of asthma and some intermittent indigestion but is otherwise well. As part of her septic workup, a chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is present in this chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic dissection","Congestive heart failure","Paraoesophageal hernia","Pericardial effusion","Pneumomediastinum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe changes seen on this chest X-ray are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eparaoesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E, suggested by the retro-cardiac opacity with gas-fluid level. Most paraoesophageal hernias are asymptomatic and are an incidental finding, as in this case. When symptomatic, patients may experience heartburn, dyspepsia or epigastric pains.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when blood enters the medial layer of the aortic wall. Patients are often symptomatic with hypertension, chest pain and a tearing sensation in their back. A chest X-ray may have several suggestive findings, including a widened mediastinum (\u0026gt;8cm), double aortic contour, irregular aortic contour and potentially a mediastinal haematoma.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with signs of fluid overload such as orthopnoea (in left ventricular failure) or ankle swelling, nature, and abdominal discomfort (in right ventricular failure). Chest X-ray findings include cardiomegaly, Kerley B lines, pulmonary congestion and interstitial edema.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial effusions\u003C/strong\u003E occur when excess fluid collects in the pericardial space. Regardless of the size of the pericardial effusion, some symptoms of impaired cardiac function such as dyspnoea and reduced exercise tolerance would be expected. An X-ray would show globular enlargement of the cardiac shadow giving a water bottle configuration, an enlarged cardio-thoracic ratio and potentially pulmonary oedema which are not present in this image.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumomediastinum\u003C/strong\u003E is the presence of air within the mediastinum. This often occurs secondary to trauma, surgery, perforation of the oesophagus or barotrauma.\u00a0Chest X-ray findings include small amounts of gas appearing as a linear or curved outlining of the mediastinal contours. It would not appear as a gas-fluid level opacity as in the picture provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paraoesophageal hernias are often an incidental finding"],"references":["Anan RA. Hiatus hernia. Radiopaedia. Updated August 12, 2022. Accessed October 6, 2022. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/hiatus-hernia","Kahrilas PJ. Paraoesophageal hernia. UpToDate. Updated January 14, 2021. Accessed October 6, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/hiatus-hernia?search=Paraoesophageal%20hernia%20\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2~13\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2#H1255385862","Kahrilas PJ, Kim HC, Pandolfino JE. Approaches to the diagnosis and grading of hiatal hernia. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2008;22(4):601-16. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18656819/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17577"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17577"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd1db441-9da8-4519-818c-42e15fce5382.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd1db441-9da8-4519-818c-42e15fce5382.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisi